 Congress read this letter on 6 Mar. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span></span>, 4:186).</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0238-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0238-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>For Congresss resolution of 22 Dec. 1775 encouraging GW to attack Boston, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0547&amp;expandNote=GEWN-03-02-02-0547-fn-0004#GEWN-03-02-02-0547-fn-0004" class="document">Hancock to GW, 22 Dec. 1775, n.4</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0238-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0238-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0229" class="document">Council of War, 16 Feb. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0238-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0238-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Thomas Mason, a ship captain and merchant from Philadelphia, went to Cambridge with Horatio Gates in July 1775 and after talking with GW promised to go to Europe for gunpowder. Forming a private venture with Robert Morris and Jacob Winey, Mason sailed from Philadelphia on 12 Aug. 1775. His schooner returned under another captain in early January 1776 with 60 tons of saltpeter, and on 2 Feb. 1776 Mason arrived off the Delaware capes in a brig loaded with 60 tons of saltpeter, 15 tons of gunpowder, and 1,300 stand of arms. See Masons journal, 10 July 17752 Feb. 1776, in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William Bell Clark et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Naval Documents of the American Revolution&lt;/i&gt;. 11 vols. to date. Washington, D.C., 1964. ]">Clark, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Naval Documents</span></span>, 1:112728, 2:730, 78991, 3:462, 1103; see also Caesar Rodney to Thomas Rodney, 4 Feb. 1776, in <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Paul H. Smith et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Letters of Delegates to Congress, 17741789&lt;/i&gt;. 26 vols. Washington, D.C., 19762000. ]">Smith, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Letters of Delegates</span></span>, 3:19496.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0238-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0238-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>William Hooper (17421790), a native of Boston who moved to Wilmington, N.C., in 1764 and was now serving as one of North Carolinas delegates to the Continental Congress, went to Cambridge about the first of this month to see his mother who had recently gotten out of Boston. Hooper was a member of Congress from the fall of 1774 to the spring of 1777 when he resigned his seat to resume his law practice in Wilmington.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-03-02-0238-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-03-03-02-0238-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>For the procurement of gunpowder from Connecticut, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0196" class="document">GW to Jonathan Trumbull, Sr., 8 Feb. (first letter)</a> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0246" class="document">19 Feb.</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0217" class="document">Trumbull to GW, 12</a>, <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0233" class="document">16 Feb.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-03-02-0231" class="document">Nicholas Cooke to GW, 16 Feb. 1776</a>.</p>

</div>
